<header class="header">
  <h1>Floating Row Cover vs Frost Blanket: Which Extends Your Season More?</h1>

  <p class="tagline">
    Similar materials — different performance depending on weight and conditions.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Floating row cover and frost blankets are often used interchangeably, but they are not identical.</strong>
    Fabric weight, insulation level, and intended use determine how much protection — and season extension — you actually gain.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cold climates, a few degrees of protection can mean the difference between
    stalled transplants and steady early growth.
    But choosing the wrong fabric may offer less protection than expected.
  </p>

  <p>
    Most lightweight row cover provides 2–4°F of buffering,
    while heavier frost blankets may offer 4–8°F under calm conditions.
    For a deeper breakdown of protection limits, see
    <a href="/guides/how-many-degrees-does-frost-cloth-protect/">how frost cloth protection actually works</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This guide compares floating row cover and frost blankets
    so you can choose the right option for extending your growing season.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Is Floating Row Cover?</h2>

  <p>
    Floating row cover is a lightweight, breathable fabric designed to rest directly on plants
    or be supported over hoops.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is commonly used for:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Pest exclusion (insects and beetles)</li>
    <li>Wind buffering</li>
    <li>Light frost protection</li>
    <li>Season extension in fall</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Typical Characteristics</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>Fabric weight around 0.5 oz per square yard</li>
    <li>High light transmission</li>
    <li>Breathable and permeable to water</li>
    <li>Can remain on during cool daytime conditions</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Because it is lightweight,
    floating row cover generally provides limited insulation —
    often in the 2–4°F range during calm nights.
  </p>

  <p>
    Its primary strength is versatility.
    It protects against insects while offering mild frost buffering,
    making it useful for cool-season crops and early fall extension.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Floating row cover prioritizes airflow and light transmission over heavy insulation.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Is a Frost Blanket?</h2>

  <p>
    A frost blanket is a heavier-weight version of row cover
    designed specifically for cold protection rather than pest exclusion.
  </p>

  <p>
    While materials are similar,
    frost blankets typically use thicker fabric to increase insulation.
  </p>

  <h3>Typical Characteristics</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>Fabric weight between 1.0 and 2.0 oz per square yard</li>
    <li>Greater insulation capacity</li>
    <li>Lower light transmission compared to lightweight row cover</li>
    <li>Often marketed for protection “down to 28°F”</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Frost blankets are most often used for:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Protecting tender spring transplants</li>
    <li>Buffering unexpected late frosts</li>
    <li>Extending harvest during early fall freezes</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Because of reduced light penetration,
    heavier frost blankets are typically installed overnight
    and removed once daytime temperatures rise.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost blankets prioritize insulation over long-term airflow and pest protection.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why “Floating Row Cover” and “Frost Blanket” Are Often Confused</h2>

  <p>
    Many manufacturers use the terms interchangeably.
  </p>

  <p>
    In practice, both materials are typically spun-bonded polypropylene fabric.
    The difference lies in fabric weight — not the label.
  </p>

  <h3>What to Look for Instead of the Name</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>Fabric weight (oz per square yard)</li>
    <li>Advertised temperature range</li>
    <li>Light transmission level</li>
    <li>Recommended use (pest control vs frost protection)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    A “frost blanket” may simply be heavier row cover.
    A “floating row cover” may be marketed for frost protection.
  </p>

  <p>
    The label matters less than the insulation level.
    If you are deciding between weights,
    review <a href="/guides/best-frost-cloth-for-vegetable-gardens/">how to choose frost cloth for cold climates</a>
    for a weight-focused breakdown.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Focus on fabric weight and use case — not terminology.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When to Use Both Together</h2>

  <p>
    In colder climates, floating row cover and frost blankets
    do not have to be mutually exclusive.
  </p>

  <p>
    Layering can increase insulation during higher-risk nights,
    especially when used over hoops to create an air pocket.
  </p>

  <h3>Layering for Added Protection</h3>

  <p>
    A common approach is:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Lightweight row cover as the base layer</li>
    <li>Heavier frost blanket added when deeper frost is forecast</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The air space between layers improves insulation,
    particularly during calm radiational frost events.
  </p>

  <h3>Low Tunnel Systems</h3>

  <p>
    Using hoops with frost blanket fabric
    creates a more stable microclimate than fabric resting directly on plants.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short growing seasons, this setup can protect early transplants
    during unpredictable spring temperature swings.
  </p>

  <p>
    However, layering does not eliminate risk during prolonged or windy freezes.
    Always monitor forecasts and remove heavy layers once temperatures rise.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Layering increases margin — not immunity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Floating Row Cover vs Frost Blanket: A Simple Decision Framework</h2>

  <p>
    Choose based on risk level, crop sensitivity, and how aggressively you are extending the season.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>What is your expected low temperature?</strong><br>
      Near 32°F → Floating row cover may be sufficient.<br>
      Upper 20s°F → Frost blanket is more reliable.
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>Is wind forecast?</strong><br>
      Wind reduces effectiveness for both.
      Heavier fabric performs slightly better when edges are sealed.
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>Are you protecting tender crops?</strong><br>
      Tomatoes and peppers benefit from heavier insulation,
      especially early in spring.
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>Do you need pest protection too?</strong><br>
      Floating row cover provides insect exclusion along with mild frost buffering.
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>How long will the cover stay in place?</strong><br>
      Lightweight row cover tolerates longer daytime coverage.
      Frost blankets are best used overnight or during short cold events.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    In most cold-climate vegetable gardens:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Floating row cover is ideal for light frost and pest control.</li>
    <li>Frost blankets extend the season further during higher-risk nights.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For a weight-focused buying guide, see
    <a href="/guides/best-frost-cloth-for-vegetable-gardens/">choosing frost cloth for vegetable gardens</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    And if you are coordinating frost protection with transplant timing,
    confirm your planting window first using
    the <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">seed starting planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Match insulation to risk. Add layers when necessary. Respect the limits.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Are floating row cover and frost blanket the same material?</summary>
    <p>
      Often yes. Both are usually spun-bonded polypropylene fabric.
      The primary difference is thickness and insulation level.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Which provides more frost protection?</summary>
    <p>
      Frost blankets generally provide more insulation due to heavier fabric weight.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Can floating row cover protect tomatoes in spring?</summary>
    <p>
      It may protect against light frost, but medium-weight frost blanket
      is usually more reliable when lows drop below 30°F.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Can I leave frost blanket on during the day?</summary>
    <p>
      Heavy frost blankets should typically be removed during warmer days
      to prevent overheating and light reduction.
    </p>
  </details>
</section>

